Register Details for AddressMap abc_soc_top/noc/syscon_m_syscon_0_0x00158000_address_map_instance

Note: AddressOffsets before register name are offsets inside AddressMap (that is what the "+" means)

+0x00000000 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_dlnk_s_hub_map_jesd_hub_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x000000f0 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_dlnk_s_pcie_map_pcie_main_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x000001b0 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_drf_0_s_ant_1_map_ant_1_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000270 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_drf_0_s_mem_fb_map_mem_fb_0_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000330 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_drf_0_s_trxant_3_map_trxant_3_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x000003c0 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_drf_0_s_trxsys_2_map_trxsys_2_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000480 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_drf_1_s_fb_ant_map_fb_ant_1_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000540 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_drf_1_s_trxant_0_map_trxant_4_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000600 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_drf_1_s_trxsys_0_map_trxsys_4_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation

Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000750 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_rcs_s_rcs_cs_map_rcs_cs_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000810 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_vex_sfc_s_v2d_2_map_v2d_2_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x000008d0 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_vex_sfc_s_v2d_6_map_v2d_6_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000990 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_vex_sfc_s_vex_2_map_vex_2_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000a20 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_vex_sfc_s_vex_dbg_1_map_vex_dgb_1_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000ae0 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_vex_sfc_s_vha_2_map_vha_2_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00000ba0 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_addr_base_mem_vex_sfc_s_vha_6_map_vha_6_0_value
Base address registers
These registers specify the base addresses and masks of different destination ranges accessible from this manager-initiator. One base, mask, and reloc register set per address range assigned to the manager-initiator. These registers are programmable only if address range programmability is enabled on this bridge through NocStudio property. When programmability is disabled, these are read-only registers with values specified through NocStudios add_range properties. A destination address range is specified using the above base address and mask pair. An address on the AR or AW channel has a match against a range if it satisfies the equation
AxADDRS and AXIM_ADDR_MASK[i] == AXIM_ADDR_BASE[i]
Note that programmed base must already factor the mask. The base should not have a 1b1 bit where the corresponding mask bit is 1b0. What this means is that the programmed base should already have performed a bit-wise AND operation with the mask. An address which doesnt match any range results in a decode error response. Note that programming of these registers must ensure that an address matches only against one range. Match against multiple ranges is a fatal error and will raise an interrupt.
Address ranges are specified at 64B cache line boundary. Lower six bits if AXIM_ADDR_BASE and AXIM_ADDR_MASK are used for specifying access permissions on an address range.

+0x00003c00 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_response_timeout_control_value
Timeout configuration register
This register is used to configure response timeouts.
AXIM_RESPONSE_TIMEOUT_CONTROL[8] En needs to be set for timeout tracking to be enabled. When this bit is 1 b0, no timestamps are recorded to generate timeout interrupts. A 64-bit free running counter is used to time the response interval.
AXIM_RESPONSE_TIMEOUT_CONTROL[5:0] TI specifies the lower bit index into this counter, from where 2-bits are picked up and recorded as the arrival time stamp of every incoming AR and AW command. If response for a command does not return before the current time stamp rolls to arrival time stamp minus 1, the response is assumed to have timedout and an interrupt is raised along with the dest ID to which the timed out request was sent.
When changing the TI field, first write to the register with the En field cleared, then write a second time with the TI field to its new value, then a 3rd write to restore the En field to Enabled. During this update while the En field is cleared, existing timers will cancelled, and new timer starts will be inhibited.

+0x00003c10 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_clk_gating_hysteresis_count_value
Clock gating hysteresis counter register
Programmable interval used by coarse clock gating logic in the bridge.This interval is used to generate heart beat pulses using noc_clk on that bridge. These heart beat pulses are broadcast to each local clock gating domain within the bridge where they are synchronized to the CG domain s clock. Four consecutive heart beat pulses in the CG domain is used as the inactivity/idle interval to initiate coarse clock gating of the CG domain.

+0x00003c20 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_autowake_power_domain_value
Configurations for autowake
Configures the bridge s support for autowake of power domains.
When set, the bridge halts a request and issues wakeup requests for power domains that need to powered up to complete the transaction. The power domains should support auto wake. When reset, the bridge issues DECERR for any transaction which has dependent power domains in sleep state.

+0x00003c40 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_qos_weight_0_value
QoS profile data
This register describes the weight value of each QoS supported at the AXI manager-initiator bridge. Each byte of this register must be greater than or equal to 1. Each transmitting bridge channels supports up to 16 QoS profiles. Each QoS is composed of priority and weight, however only the weight is programmable, therefore is part of the registers.QoS data is composed of two registers, axim_qos_weight_0 and axim_qos_weight_1, each of which contains the weight of eight profiles. Depending upon how many QoS profiles are enabled, the appropriate bits in the following registers are available.

+0x00003d00 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_event_status_value
Status flag register
When reordering is disabled on the bridge, hazard stall occurs if the initiator tries to access a new target device while response from a different target is outstanding on the same AID.
This is because the responses can arrive out of order and the bridge is not equipped to correct the order. Without re-order buffers, hazard stalls also occur if a new large command needs to be split while there are older commands outstanding, or a large command just finished sending all its split segments but all responses have not returned yet.
When reordering is enabled, stall due to hazard occurs if a new command arrives, whose NoC QoS is different from the NoC QoS of commands outstanding on that AID.

+0x00003e00 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_error_interrupt_status_strg_value
Status and error register
These error status bits record the first error event and have to be cleared by writing a 1 b0 before new errors are recorded. For flop structure parity error interrupts, the AXIM_LOG_FLOPPARITY_ERROR register should be cleared by writing it to zero before the flop structure parity interrupt bit is cleared in this register.

+0x00003e40 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_error_interrupt_mask_value
Interrupt mask registers
Interrupt mask register. Individual bit position matches the error bit positions in AXIM_ERROR_INTERRUPT_STATUS. When an INTM bit is set, occurrence of the corresponding error event will not cause an interrupt to be raised. When 1 b0, error event will cause interrupt to be raised.

+0x00003e80 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_response_timeout_destid_value
Destination ID of timed out requests
AR destid and AW destid fields indicate destination IDs to which a read, write response timeout was detected.
Note that destid encoding is not same as the bridge ID of the destination. NocStudio provides a table mapping the destids to the actual destination ports accessible from the manager-initiator bridge.

+0x00003f08 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_event_capture_addr_mask_value
Address capture mask
If command address on the AR, AW channel logically ANDed with this mask is equal to the value specified in AXIM_EVENT_CAPTURE_ADDR, then an address match has occurred. Note that only lowest significant bits equal to the initiator s address width are used in the comparison.

Count of captured event

+0x00003f28 Register(64 bit) bridge_syscon_m_syscon_0_6_10_axim_count_for_latency_0_value
Number of captured commands over which latency is to be measured
This register is programmed with the number of commands over which latency is to be measured. When this register counts down to 0, latency measurement is complete and average latency can be computed using:
Average command latency = Value in AXIM_EVENT_COUNTER_0/Value which was programmed in AXIM_COUNT_FOR_LATENCY_0
There are two sets of counters available for gathering statistics. AXIM_EVENT_CAPTURE_COMMAND_1, AXIM_EVENT_CAPTURE_COMMAND_MASK_1, AXIM_EVENT_COUNTER_1, AXIM_COUNT_FOR_LATENCY_1 constitute the second bank of counters and are similar to the above set.
